 mil:`A genuine state-change from "framework announced" to "framework signed" — but every serious read says it won't hold. The trilateral framework was signed June 26 in Washington (5th round): IDF withdraws from two pilot zones, the Lebanese Armed Forces take over and oversee Hezbollah disarmament. Yet violence continued: Hezbollah killed IDF Cpt. David Hazutt (21) at Deir Siryan June 28, wounded four soldiers at Beit Yahoun, and a car-bomb assassination attempt struck Holon inside Israel. Israel blew a 200m Hezbollah drone tunnel under Majdal Zoun with announced plans for 500 tons of explosives under Beaufort Ridge.`,
 pol:`Katz (Jun 28): Israel has "no territorial ambitions" but won't withdraw "a millimeter" beyond the two pilot zones until Hezbollah is disarmed — "people should not hold their breath." Hezbollah's Qassem called the framework "null and void," a "surrender," vowed to keep fighting, and called the US-Iran deal an "official declaration of defeat." A Haaretz analysis warns the deal could make southern Lebanon a "Gaza Strip 2" — indefinite Israeli presence, expanding controlled zone, no realistic disarmament path; Article 7 excludes Iran, contradicting the Swiss understandings. Prediction-market odds of a permanent deal by June 30 fell to 1.4%.`,
 eco:`The Lebanon→energy-market transmission remains weak (established in v10), so this stays a political track. Over 1M displaced (>20% of Lebanon's population). A durable framework would remove the most-cited derailment risk to the Iran settlement — but implementation odds are very low.`,
