 assess:`Lebanon ticks back up 74→76 — counterintuitively, because the framework got signed. The signing is real (the first Israel-Lebanon framework since the 1983 May 17 Agreement), but the Diplomatic Track makes the trap visible: of its three negotiation strands, one is signed (the framework), one has already collapsed (Hezbollah disarmament, rejected as "null & void"), and one is stalled (the move-vs-move mechanism). The serious analytic consensus — Katz's "not a millimeter," Haaretz's "Gaza Strip 2," the 1.4% market odds — is that the signed paper institutionalizes an indefinite Israeli presence rather than resolving anything. The index rises because a signed-but-rejected framework with continued killings is more volatile, not less, than open talks.`
